<subSubSection type="etymology">
<paragraph pageNumber="452">
Etymology L 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181900" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole mera Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole mera Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="452" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mera">mera</taxonomicName>
, pure, unadulterated, referring to the color.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageNumber="452">
diagnosis A medium-sized yellow species whose major has an elongate head, shallow scrobes, deep occipital cleft, semicircular promesonotal profile, and comulate postpetiole. Similar to 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33652" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole casta Wheeler" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole casta Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="452" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="casta">casta</taxonomicName>
, but the 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181900" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole mera Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole mera Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="452" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mera">mera</taxonomicName>
major differs in its carinulate and deeply cleaved occiput, oblique orientation of the carinulae mesad to the eyes, and more bulbous promesonotal profile.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="description">
<paragraph pageNumber="452">measurements (mm) Holotype major: HW 0.80, HL 0.94, SL 0.42, EL 0.14, PW 0.50. Paratype minor: HW 0.44, HL 0.46, SL 0.38, EL 0.08, PW 0.26. Color Major and minor: concolorous clear yellow.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="distribution">
<paragraph pageNumber="452">range Central and southern Texas (Cameron, Hidalgo, and Travis counties).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
